================================================================================
3. FINDINGS
================================================================================

FINDING-01 [CRITICAL]
----------------------
Title      : Cargo.lock excluded from version control
Description: The .gitignore file explicitly ignores Cargo.lock. For binary
             applications (as opposed to libraries), Cargo documentation
             recommends committing Cargo.lock to ensure reproducible builds.
             Without it, dependency versions may drift between developer
             machines, CI, and release environments.
Impact     : Builds may produce different binary outputs across environments.
             Security-sensitive dependency version pinning is lost. CI could
             silently adopt different transitive dependency versions.
Root Cause : The .gitignore entry "Cargo.lock" is appropriate for library
             crates but not for binary applications. This is a common mistake
             when bootstrapping Rust projects.

FINDING-02 [WARNING]
---------------------
Title      : Template field stored but never used in rendering
Description: Both HtmlStrategy and PdfStrategy accept an optional template
             name and store it in a field (self.template). However, neither
             strategy uses this value when invoking pandoc — the template is
             silently ignored. The Tera engine is initialised in commands/build.rs
             but its output is never passed to any strategy or used in rendering.
Impact     : Users who specify a template in renderflow.yaml will receive no
             error and no indication that the template was not applied.
             Custom templates are effectively non-functional.
Root Cause : The template rendering integration is incomplete. The architecture
             allocates the capability but the wiring between Tera, strategies,
             and pandoc has not been implemented.

FINDING-03 [WARNING]
---------------------
Title      : Pipeline::run() is unused; build.rs calls phases separately
Description: The Pipeline struct exposes a combined run() method that executes
             transforms then steps in sequence. However, commands/build.rs
             calls run_transforms() and run_steps() separately. The public
             run() method is dead code in practice.
Impact     : Mild API inconsistency and potential for divergence. The combined
             run() method could silently become out of sync with how the build
             command actually uses the pipeline.
Root Cause : The split was likely introduced to support dry-run mode, which
             runs transforms but skips steps. The run() method was not
             removed or marked appropriately after this split.

FINDING-04 [MINOR]
-------------------
Title      : EmojiTransform is the only registered transform
Description: The transform pipeline architecture supports multiple pluggable
             in-memory transforms, but only EmojiTransform is implemented and
             registered. The design anticipates more transforms (e.g., footnote
             expansion, variable substitution, syntax highlighting prep) but
             none exist.
Impact     : Limited document transformation capability. Users who expect
             richer pre-processing pipelines will find the system underpowered.
Root Cause : V1 implementation scope. The architecture is correct; it simply
             lacks additional transform implementations.

FINDING-05 [MINOR]
-------------------
Title      : No DOCX output format despite Roadmap listing it
Description: The README roadmap lists "DOCX output format" as a planned
             feature. The OutputType enum only has Html and Pdf variants.
             Any attempt to use type: docx in a config produces a YAML
             parse error rather than a helpful "not yet supported" message.
Impact     : Confusing error experience for users who read the roadmap and
             attempt to use DOCX output.
Root Cause : Feature is planned but not implemented. Error handling in the
             config parsing layer does not distinguish between unknown types
             and unsupported-but-planned types.

================================================================================
4. SUGGESTED FIXES
================================================================================

FIX-01 → addresses FINDING-01
-------------------------------
Title  : Commit Cargo.lock to version control
Steps  :
  1. Remove "Cargo.lock" from .gitignore
  2. Run: cargo generate-lockfile
  3. Add and commit Cargo.lock: git add Cargo.lock && git commit
  4. Update contributing documentation to note that Cargo.lock is tracked
Note   : This is the official Cargo recommendation for binary crates.
         See: https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/faq.html#why-do-binaries-have-cargolock-in-version-control-but-not-libraries

FIX-02 → addresses FINDING-02
-------------------------------
Title  : Wire template rendering into strategy execution
Steps  :
  1. Pass the initialised Tera instance from commands/build.rs into each
     strategy (e.g., via constructor or a StrategyConfig struct)
  2. In HtmlStrategy::render(), if self.template is Some(name), use Tera to
     render a wrapper template around the pandoc output
  3. Alternatively, pass --template to pandoc directly for HTML templates
  4. Add integration tests that verify template application
Note   : The Tera engine is already initialised in build.rs — it only needs
         to be threaded through to the strategy layer.

FIX-03 → addresses FINDING-03
-------------------------------
Title  : Align Pipeline API with actual usage pattern
Steps  :
  Option A: Remove Pipeline::run() and document that callers use
            run_transforms() + run_steps() separately (supports dry-run)
  Option B: Extend Pipeline::run() to accept a dry_run flag so callers
            can use the unified API
  Option C: Mark Pipeline::run() with #[allow(dead_code)] and a doc comment
            explaining when it is appropriate to use
Recommendation: Option A is simplest and removes dead code.

FIX-04 → addresses FINDING-04
-------------------------------
Title  : Implement additional document transforms
Steps  :
  1. Add a VariableSubstitutionTransform to support {{variable}} replacement
     using values from the config or a separate variables map
  2. Add a SyntaxHighlightTransform to pre-process fenced code blocks
  3. Register new transforms in commands/build.rs
Note   : The trait-based architecture makes this straightforward — implement
         the Transform trait and add to the pipeline.

FIX-05 → addresses FINDING-05
-------------------------------
Title  : Improve error message for unsupported output types
Steps  :
  1. Add a DocxPlanned variant to OutputType (or use a raw string fallback)
  2. In select_strategy(), match on planned-but-unimplemented types and
     return a descriptive error: "DOCX output is not yet supported. Track
     progress at: <issue link>"
  3. Alternatively, handle unknown type strings in the YAML deserializer
     with a custom error message before validation

================================================================================
5. POSITIVE OBSERVATIONS
================================================================================

OBSERVATION-01: Clean Pipeline Architecture
  The two-phase pipeline (transforms → steps) is well-designed. The separation
  between pure in-memory transforms and I/O-bound steps is architecturally sound
  and enables dry-run mode with zero additional code paths.

OBSERVATION-02: Excellent Error Propagation
  The use of anyhow with with_context() throughout produces actionable,
  human-readable error messages. Errors include the failing program name, exit
  code, and stderr output — exactly what a developer needs to diagnose failures.

OBSERVATION-03: Partial-Failure Resilience in Build
  commands/build.rs collects failed outputs rather than bailing on the first
  failure. This means a failed PDF render does not prevent a successful HTML
  render, and vice versa. The final error aggregates all failures clearly.

OBSERVATION-04: Comprehensive Test Coverage
  Every major module has unit tests. Integration tests cover CLI flags,
  build command behaviour, and pipeline end-to-end flows. Tests are well-named
  and use appropriate helpers (tempfile, NamedTempFile) to avoid filesystem
  pollution.

OBSERVATION-05: Asset Path Normalization
  The normalize_asset_paths function handles relative paths, absolute paths,
  URL schemes (http/https/ftp/data), and inline title attributes. The logic
  is robust and has thorough test coverage including edge cases.

OBSERVATION-06: Developer Workflow Tooling
  The Taskfile.yml provides a consistent set of named tasks (build, test,
  lint, format, check, clean) that make the development workflow discoverable
  and repeatable without memorising cargo commands.

OBSERVATION-07: Strategy Pattern for Output Formats
  The OutputStrategy trait allows new output formats to be added without
  modifying the pipeline or build orchestration logic. This is the correct
  extension point for future formats (DOCX, EPUB, etc.).

OBSERVATION-08: Tectonic Check Before Rendering
  PdfStrategy::check_tectonic() performs an early availability check with a
  clear, actionable error message before attempting to invoke pandoc. This
  prevents confusing downstream failures when tectonic is not installed.

================================================================================
6. SYSTEM READINESS
================================================================================

Status: CONDITIONAL

The core document rendering pipeline is functional and well-tested. The system
can reliably convert Markdown to HTML and PDF (given pandoc and tectonic are
installed). The codebase follows consistent patterns and has good error
handling.

The CONDITIONAL status is due to:
  1. Cargo.lock absent from version control — reproducible builds not guaranteed
  2. Template system declared but not wired — advertised feature is non-functional

Recommended actions before marking READY:
  [ ] FIX-01: Commit Cargo.lock (low effort, high value)
  [ ] FIX-02: Complete template rendering integration (medium effort)
  [ ] FIX-03: Resolve Pipeline::run() dead code (low effort)

